WHERE nums = 3)

SELECT 
(SELECT COUNT(*) FROM FirstCustomers) FirstCustomerTotal,
(SELECT COUNT(*) FROM SecondCustomers) SecondCustomerTotal,
(SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ThirdCustomers) ThirdCustomerTotal,
COUNT(*)
	
FROM FirstCustomers LEFT JOIN SecondCustomers 
ON FirstCustomers.customer_id = SecondCustomers.customer_id

LEFT JOIN ThirdCustomers
ON FirstCustomers.customer_id = ThirdCustomers.customer_id

WHERE (strftime('%Y', SecondCustomers.new_order_date) - strftime('%Y', FirstCustomers.new_order_date)) * 12 +
    (strftime('%m', SecondCustomers.new_order_date) - strftime('%m', FirstCustomers.new_order_date)) BETWEEN 0 AND 1 -- second time less than 2 months since first
AND (strftime('%Y', ThirdCustomers.new_order_date) - strftime('%Y', SecondCustomers.new_order_date)) * 12 +
    (strftime('%m', ThirdCustomers.new_order_date) - strftime('%m', SecondCustomers.new_order_date)) BETWEEN 0 AND 1 -- third time less than 2 months since second


ANALYSIS:

There are 747 ThirdCustomers, down from 793 First and 781 Second.
The amount of people who also went to shop a third time soon after the first two was only 14.
This is 13.33% of those who appeared in the 105 prior who soon shopped a second time, and 1.77% of all customers. 

The drastic fall-off shares a lot about the issues with the superstore's current system with optimising profits. 
Currently, there is little incentive for new shoppers compared to already frequent shoppers, and the odds of a shopper coming back soon is very unlikely.

